{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"90df181b-27b5-47b8-9a16-649c8077b2e4","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe developer report confirms the bottleneck is **MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation — not compilation itself. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps a long-lived MSBuild host process in memory.\n\nHere are the recommended fixes, in order of impact:\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Server (biggest win)\n\nSet this environment variable to keep MSBuild nodes alive between CLI invocations, just like VS does:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\nThis eliminates repeated JIT warmup and project re-evaluation costs.\n\n### 2. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\n\nInstead of repeatedly running `dotnet build`, use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\nThis keeps the build process hot and triggers incremental rebuilds on file save — the closest CLI equivalent to VS's background build.\n\n### 3. Ensure shared Roslyn compilation is enabled\n\nAdd to the `.csproj` to keep the Roslyn compiler server alive across builds:\n\n```xml\n<UseSharedCompilation>true</UseSharedCompilation>\n```\n\n### 4. Recommended `.csproj` change\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <UseSharedCompilation>true</UseSharedCompilation>\n  <ProduceReferenceAssembly>true</ProduceReferenceAssembly>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n`ProduceReferenceAssembly` helps downstream projects skip recompilation when only method bodies change.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The VS advantage is its long-lived build host. The CLI equivalent is `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` + `dotnet watch`. Together these should bring CLI no-change builds from 2–4s down to near-instant.\n\nWant me to apply the `.csproj` changes?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e93f451c-1ce8-4a5c-93b0-ccdb84a4dcd1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer report says that `dotnet build` from CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've verified that analyzers aren't the issue, incremental build targets work correctly, and compilation itself is fast (<500ms). The overhead is from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio keeps an MSBuild server process alive (warm), so it doesn't pay the startup cost on each build. The CLI equivalent of this is the **MSBuild Server** (also known as the MSBuild build server or `dotnet build-server`).\n \nTo fix this, I should enable the MSBuild build server by setting `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or using the `BuildServer` property—this is the most impactful change and available in .NET 8+. This keeps the MSBuild process warm between builds, eliminating the JIT and project re-evaluation overhead that's causing the slowdown.\n\nI should also enable Roslyn's shared compilation with `<UseSharedCompilation>true</UseSharedCompilation>` to avoid recompiling the compiler itself each time. For development workflows, `dotnet watch` keeps the build hot during the inner loop, and for multi-project solutions, the `-graph` flag can optimize how projects are built together.","outputTokens":1155,"requestId":"7407:23E21D:15EA2CF:1872F34:6A051DA9"},"id":"eda2a67a-5901-4978-8566-e2fd8f42beee","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:56:32.479Z","parentId":"a7946283-f37d-46aa-ad83-353c62ab6471"}
